The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that electoral irregularities would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terrorism.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe became victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats from the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is attributable to the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
As a result of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), was unable to reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas.
Moreover, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, unable to cast their ballots.
I continue to doubt the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from placing observers at 52% of the rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party was missing observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will at these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
Even at this early stage of our investigations, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most of the votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential election, in which the incumbent president, Robert Mugabe, emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is seen as illegitimate by them.
The people of Zimbabwe have been deprived of their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to have this recognized.
Perhaps it is not yet too late for that.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Perhaps the government wants to arrest me.
I was already arrested before the elections for treason.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people to reclaim their rights and power.
It is in our hands to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
Political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger of the news.
Should that happen, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to remain strong and to finish what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who did not let themselves be sent away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together in order to achieve democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply let these elections stand, but they must also not fall into Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, legitimate change in the constitution, in the legal system, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that throughout Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African states, irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always some kind of crisis because of elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to underhanded means when it is time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in their hour of greatest need.
I pledge not to abandon them.
